-tower-yangon.com/ | title=About Sakura Tower | date=2020-04-16}}, it is a 100-meter high 20-story tower, completed in 1999. <br/> A 2014 National Geographic article, {{cite journal | url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/news/2014/11/141112-myanmar-burma-yangon-rangoon-heritage-architecture/ | title=The Race to Save Architecture in Myanmar's Biggest City | journal=The National Geographic | date=2014-11-13}}, identifies the Sakura Tower as the tallest building in Yangon.</ref>\n|-\n| [[Sedona Hotel II]]\n| \n| [[Yangon]]\n| ~{{convert|104|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| 29\n| 2016\u20132018\n| \n| <ref name=emporis/>\n|-\n| [[Golden City, Yangon|Golden City I]] \n| \n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[Yangon]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" | {{convert|109.7|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 33\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2018\u20132019\n| rowspan=\"4\" | \n| rowspan=\"4\" | <ref name=dp-gc/>\n|-\n| [[Golden City, Yangon|Golden City II]]\n| \n|-\n| [[Golden City, Yangon|Golden City III]]\n| \n|-\n| [[Golden City, Yangon|Golden City IV]]\n| \n|-\n| [[Diamond Inya Palace]]\n| \n| [[Yangon]]\n| ~{{convert|122|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| 34\n| 2019\u2013present\n| \n| <ref name=emporis/>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of tallest structures in Myanmar]]\n* [[List of tallest buildings in Yangon]]\n\n==External sources==\n* [https://www.cqhp.org/ Committee for Quality Control of High Rise Building Construction Projects, Republic of the Union of Myanmar]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{TBSW}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tallest Buildings in Myanmar, List Of}}\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Architecture of Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Lists of tallest buildings in Asia|Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Lists of tallest structures by country|Myanmar]]\n", "name_user": "Hybernator", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_tallest_buildings_in_Myanmar"}
{"title_page": "Guy Hibbert", "text_new": "{{short description|British screenwriter|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Guy Hibbert\n| image        = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1950|7|27}}\n| birth_place  = [[Oxford]], England\n| nationality  = British\n| other_names  = \n| occupation   = Screenwriter, film producer\n| years_active =\n| known_for    = \n| spouse       = [[Lia Williams (2005-2020)]]\n| children     = 1\n}}\n\n'''Guy Hibbert''' (born 27 July 1950) is a British [[screenwriter]]. He has won four [[Bafta]] TV awards. \n\nHe wrote the 2009 film ''[[Five Minutes of Heaven]]''. This film was premiered at the [[25th Sundance Film Festival]], where Hibbert won the World Cinema Screenwriting Award.<ref name=latimes>{{cite news|last1=Turan|first1=Kenneth|title=Nightmarish 'Push' a triple Sundance winner|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jan/25/entertainment/et-sundance25|accessdate=14 January 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|date=25 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nHibbert lives in London. He has one child, Celeste.\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[Shot Through the Heart]]'' (1998) \u2013 writer\n* ''[[May 33rd]]'' (2004) \u2013 writer and executive producer\n* ''[[Omagh (film)|Omagh]]'' (2004) \u2013 co-writer with [[Paul Greengrass]]\n* ''[[Who Gets the Dog? (ITV drama)|Who Gets the Dog?]]'' (2007) \u2013 writer \n* ''[[Five Minutes of Heaven]]'' (2009) \u2013 writer\n* ''[[Complicit (film)|Complicit]]'' (2013) \u2013 writer and executive producer\n* ''[[Eye in the Sky (2015 film)|Eye in the Sky]]'' (2015) \u2013 writer\n* ''[[A United Kingdom]]'' (2016) - writer and executive producer\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0382505}}\n*{{BFI|id=4ce2ba37c29c3|name=Guy Hibbert<!--using name parameter to prevent italic text-->}}\n\n{{John Whiting Award|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hibbert, Guy}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Sundance Film Festival award winners]]\n[[Category:Christopher Ewart-Biggs Memorial Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:People from Oxford]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British screenwriter|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Guy Hibbert\n| image        = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1950|7|27}}\n| birth_place  = [[Oxford]], England\n| nationality  = British\n| other_names  = \n| occupation   = Screenwriter, film producer\n| years_active =\n| known_for    = \n| spouse       = [[Lia Williams (2005-2020)]]\n| children     = 1\n}}\n\n'''Guy Hibbert''' (born 27 July 1950) is a British [[screenwriter]]. He has won four [[Bafta]] TV awards. \n\nHe wrote the 2009 film ''[[Five Minutes of Heaven]]''. This film was premiered at the [[25th Sundance Film Festival]], where Hibbert won the World Cinema Screenwriting Award.<ref name=latimes>{{cite news|last1=Turan|first1=Kenneth|title=Nightmarish 'Push' a triple Sundance winner|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jan/25/entertainment/et-sundance25|accessdate=14 January 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|date=25 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nHibbert is married to the actress [[Lia Williams]] and lives in [[West Hampstead]].<ref name=cnj>{{cite news|last1=Foot|first1=Tom|title=The garden of delight for Bafta-winning Lia|url=http://www.thecnj.com/review/030906/feature030906_02.html|accessdate=14 January 2015|work=Camden New Journal}}</ref> He has one child, Celeste.\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[Shot Through the Heart]]'' (1998) \u2013 writer\n* ''[[May 33rd]]'' (2004) \u2013 writer and executive producer\n* ''[[Omagh (film)|Omagh]]